@endnode

@NODE "IntroText" "INTRODUCTION"

INTRODUCTION

Welcome to InterSpread, a fast and reliable spreadsheet program specially
written for your Amiga!

Thank you for buying an InterActivision product. Once you have learned how
to use it, it will prove to be a flexible and powerful tool, and one which
we hope you will keep on using for a long time to come.  

INTERSPREAD IS NOT ALONE 

InterSpread is a very useful and powerful program on its own, but it also
has the ability to exchange information with its word processing
counterpart, InterWord. Blocks of figures can thus be directly imported
into a document written on the word processor without having to enter them
in manually, a great timecsaver when preparing a report or project!  

@endnode

@NODE "APPENDIX B" "Description of mathematical functions"

DESCRIPTION OF MATHEMATICAL FUNCTIONS  

This chapter describes, in alphabetical order, InterSpread's numerous
mathematical functions. There are functions for trigonometry, calculations
of interest, determination of the largest or smallest number in a list,
calculation of dates, and many more.

Most functions require an argument, ie, a value, or values, on which to
perform the calculation. These are shown in brackets after the function
name, and an example is given to show you how to use the function in your
spreadsheets. For instance, the Sine function could take the forms SIN(2),
SIN(A1), or SIN(A1+2).

As you can see, arguments can consist of values, cells, or expressions; a
few functions, however, such as SUM() and MUL() always require cells as
arguments.

Some functions require more than one argument. These are shown separated
by a colon, eg. SUM(A1:C2) which calculates the sum of cells A1, A2, B1,
B2, C1 and C2.

Other functions demand no specific number of arguments, eg. MAX(list)
which determines the largest number in a given list, eg.MAX(7:3+A5:B7:3).

Some functions require that an argument falls within certain parameters,
called a definition set. Where this is the case, the definition set will
be indicated.

Example of a definition set:
   def.s.:[-1;+1]

def.s. is the abbreviation for definition set, and the contents of the
brackets have the following meaning:

   def.s.:[from;to]

Therefore the above example would indicate that the argument must fall
between -1 and +1.

The start bracket can have either of the following meanings:
   [  from and including
   ]  from, but not including

The end bracket is used in the following way, i.e.
   ]  up to and including
   [  up to but not including

The definition set may also be indicated by greater than (>) or smaller
than (<) symbols, eg. def.s.:x>0 which means that x, the argument, must be
greater than zero.

If no definition set is indicated, there are no limitations on the value
which can be entered as an argument; however should an illegal value be
entered, InterSpread will warn you with an error message.

You may not be familiar with all of these functions, and a full description
of them falls outside the scope of this manual. If you wish to clarify the
meanings of the more unusual mathematical functions, you will find a
mathematics reference book helpful.

Descriptions of all InterSpread's mathematical functions are listed below.

