   Stop Macro                      - Shift/F2
   Name Macro                      - Alt/F6
   Name Macro Right                - Alt/F7
   Name Macro Left                 - Alt/F8
   Name Macro Down                 - Alt/F9
   Erase Macro Name                - Alt/F4
   Debug Mode                      - Alt/F4

NON-MENU SHORTCUTS 
Some of InterSpread's commonly used functions can be selected from the
keyboard using the following keys:

   Move to cell A1                            - Amiga/7
   Move to the last entry in the spreadsheet  - Amiga/1
   Move up one page                           - Amiga/9
   Move down one page                         - Amiga/3 

If you have a numeric keypad you will see the words HOME, END, PG UP and 
PG DN written on the front of the appropriate number keys to help you 
remember which is which, and you can use either the numbers on the 
numeric keypad or your qwerty keyboard. Owners of A600 machines with no 
numeric keypad will have to take our word for this, but don't worry, you 
can use InterSpread just as well without one!

   O.K. GADGET - F1
   CLOSE WINDOW - ESC
   SHIFT/UP - The first press moves the cursor to the top of the screen, 
      each following press moves it half a screen up.
   SHIFT/DOWN  - The first press moves the cursor to the bottom of the 
      screen, each following press moves it half a screen down.
   SHIFT/RIGHT - The first press moves the cursor to the extreme right 
      of the screen, each following press moves it one column further 
      right.
   SHIFT/LEFT - The first press moves the cursor to the extreme left of 
      the screen, each following press moves it one column further left.

@endnode

@NODE "APPENDIX E" "Glossary"

GLOSSARY  


Absolute cell reference - A reference within a formula or macro which
   refers only to a specific cell. No matter which cell the formula is 
   placed in, it will still refer to the same cell. See Relative cell 
   reference.

Cell - An area on the spread sheet identified as the junction of a row 
   and a column. Each cell may contain numbers, formulas, macros or text 
   (labels). The contents of one cell can be used to modify the contents 
   of another using formulas or macros. They can also be used to execute 
   command functions such as opening menus and making selections.

Cell Block - A cell block is a square or rectangular group of cells upon
   which operations and calculations may be performed. A cell block is 
   defined using two cell references, one indicating its upper leftchand 
   corner, and the other its lower rightchand corner.

Cell Cursor - The cursor which is used to indicate the currently selected
   cell. When a cell block is highlighted, the cell cursor disappears.

Cell Reference - The cocordinates that are given to identify a cell's
   location. A cell reference always consists of two parts; a letter or
   letters that specify the cell's column, and one or more digits that
   indicates its row number. For example, reference AG67 refers to column 
   AG, row 67. The columns are sequentially lettered from AcZ, then AAcZZ 
   and finally AAAcZZZ. Rows are numbered between 1 and 9999. This gives 
   a total of nearly 30 million cells!

Current Sheet - This expression mainly applies when talking about the
   status of a spreadsheet. InterSpread can handle up to 10 of them at 
   a time, of which two may be visible simultaneously. However, obviously 
   you can only physically work on one spreadsheet at a time. Whichever 
   one the cursor resides in, is known as the current sheet. All menu, 
   mouse and keyboard operations only apply to the current sheet, although 
   macros may be used to transfer data between the current sheet and any 
   other, regardless of whether they are visible or not.

Cursor - In the input line, the cursor is a small flashing block that
   indicates where entries will appear when a key is pressed. See Cell 
   cursor for further information. 

Cycle Gadget - A cycle gadget offers you a way of choosing one of numerous
   options without having to display all of them at once. Each time you 
   click the gadget, the next option is displayed, and when you are happy 
   with the current option, simply stop clicking.

File Name - The identifying title given to any file stored on disk or in
   RAM, regardless of its type. File names are obviously essential so that 
   you can distinguish one file from another.

Gadget - Although the word gadget may have various meanings according to
   the program being used, in InterSpread a gadget is a button that 
   performs a particular function when clicked upon using the mouse.

Highlight - A highlight is simply InterSpread's way of indicating that
   something has been selected, be it a cell block or a menu option.
   Highlights are usually shown in inverted (negative) colours.

Icon - An icon is a small picture designed to illustrate its function or
   contents.

Keyboard short-cut - A combination of keys, which when pressed, perform
   a function or operation that would otherwise require use of the mouse 
   and usually a menu selection.

Labels - Any text in a cell which is not a macro or a cell reference
   (within a formula) is considered to be a label, so called because 
   such entries are primarily used to label rows or columns for easier 
   reading.

Load - To transfer a file or spreadsheet from disk or RAM and into 
   InterSpread's memory.

Margin - A page has absolute dimensions beyond which text cannot be 
   printed, either because the printer's heads cannot move any further 
   or because if they could, they would be printing off the edge of the 
   paper. Margins are user-defined borders within the absolute dimensions 
   of the page, which create areas of white space around a printed 
   spreadsheet.

Pointer - The small red arrow controlled by the mouse and used to make 
   selections from menus or on-screen gadgets and requesters. It may also
   be used to indicate where you want the cursor to be positioned.

Relative Cell Reference - A reference within a formula or macro which 
   changes according to the cell it is in. For example, the formula 
   SUM(A1:A3) may be used in cell A4, but if the same formula is copied 
   to cell B4 it will automatically be changed to SUM(B1:B3). See also 
   Absolute Cell Reference.

Requester - Any window which appears and requires you to take some action.

Save - In InterSpread, Save means to store the current spreadsheet on disk
  or in RAM.

Style tag - A marker which indicates that the appearance of subsequent
   characters have been modified. Styles include bold, underline and
   superscript.

Text gadget/requester - Text gadgets and requesters appear when you need 
   to enter some text so that InterSpread can perform an operation. For 
   example, when you select Page Number from the Layout menu, a text 
   gadget/requester appears so that you can enter the starting page 
   number.

@endnode

@node "AREXX" "AREXX INTERFACE"

The inclusion of an ARexx interface makes InterSpread Pro a highly
versatile and powerful application.

SENDING COMMANDS TO INTERSPREAD
If you want to access InterSpread from within your script, you must
firstspecify the InterSpread ARexx port "InterSpread1" with the
"ADDRESS"command like this:

ADDRESS INTERSPREAD1
All commands on subsequent lines of your script are automatically
directed to InterSpread until a new Address command is encountered.

If you only want to issue a single command to InterSpread, type the
Address command on the same line as the required command. For example,
the following line will execute the BEEP command:

ADDRESS INTERSPREAD1 'BEEP'
If there's a second copy of InterSpread running, its ARexx port is 
identified as "INTERSPREAD2", whilst a third copy of the program will
be"INTERSPREAD3" and so on.

RECEIVING INFORMATION BACK FROM INTERSPREAD
Some InterSpread ARexx commands return data to the ARexx interpreter.
In order for it to receive these properly, you must activate two way 
communications between ARexx and InterSpread by including the
following line at the beginning of your script:

'OPTIONS' RESULTS
Any results which are returned from an InterSpread command will now
bestored in the ARexx variable result.

ERROR TRAPPING
Commands can sometimes fail, for example if you try to load a sheet
that doesn't exist. It's possible to find out whether an ARexx command
has failed by checking the contents of the ARexx variable rc, which is
given avalue every time a command is called.

If a command is executed without errors, rc will hold 0, but if the
command has failed, rc will contain a value greater than 0.

If a command generates an error message, the message is held in the
variable interword.lasterror.

INTERSPREAD AREXX COMMANDS
Commands may be entered in upper or lower case, but are documented
here in capitals to distinguish them from their descriptions.

The commands have been separated into two categories; 
   unique ARexxcommands, and commands that emulate menu items.

UNIQUE AREXX COMMANDS
@{"BEEP" link "BEEP"} 
@{"CELL_MOVE" link "CELL_MOVE"}
@{"CURRENT_CELL" link "CURRENT_CELL"}
@{"CURRENT_SHEETNAME" link "CURRENT_SHEETNAME"}
@{"CURRENT_SHEETNUMBER" link "CURRENT_SHEETNUMBER"}
@{"CURRENT_SHEETPATH" link "CURRENT_SHEETPATH"}
@{"GET_CELL_RESULT" link "GET_CELL_RESULT"}
@{"GET_CELL_TYPE" link "GET_CELL_TYPE"}
@{"GET_CELL_VALUE" link "GET_CELL_VALUE"}
@{"GET_COLOR" link "GET_COLOR"}
@{"HOW_MANY_SHEETS" link "HOW_MANY_SHEETS"}
@{"INFO" link "INFO"}
@{"NUMREQ" link "NUMREQ"}
@{"SET_CELL_VALUE" link "SET_CELL_VALUE"}
